<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="47" type="etymology">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="47">Etymology.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="47">
The species name refers to the clear affinity of this taxon to the genus 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Loasaceae" genus="Klaprothia" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Klaprothia" order="Cornales" pageId="0" pageNumber="47" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="47">Klaprothia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Kunth.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="47" type="distribution">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="47">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="47">
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Loasaceae" genus="Xylopodia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Xylopodia klaprothioides" order="Cornales" pageId="0" pageNumber="47" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="klaprothioides">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="47">Xylopodia klaprothioides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is restricted to a small area of the Pacific slope of the Cordillera Occidental in Andean NW Peru. It is a very narrowly endemic species, known from only two localities some 8 km apart (in a direct line) in Dpto. Cajamarca Prov. 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Contumazá">Contumaza</normalizedToken>
, at elevations from ca. 2,500-3,000 m (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 1" captionStartId="F1" captionText="Figure 1. Known distribution of Xylopodia klaprothioides and X. laurensis (photo credit for La Paz: A. F. Fuentes)." figureDoi="10.3897/phytokeys.194.77827.figure1" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/673018" pageId="0" pageNumber="47">1</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="47" type="ecology">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="47">Ecology.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="47">
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Loasaceae" genus="Xylopodia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Xylopodia klaprothioides" order="Cornales" pageId="0" pageNumber="47" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="klaprothioides">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="47">Xylopodia klaprothioides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
occurs in seasonally dry Andean scrub habitats, mostly around hedges and gullies, often on rocky soil dominated by xeric adapted shrubs, small trees and other vegetation including 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Loasaceae" genus="Cylindropuntia" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Cylindropuntia" order="Cornales" pageId="0" pageNumber="47" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="47">Cylindropuntia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Engelm.) F.M. Knuth and terrestrial bromeliads (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 4" captionStartId="F4" captionText="Figure 4. Habitats of Xylopodia. A deciduous forest near Jujuy, Argentina, habitat of X. laurensis B X. laurensis habitat in a dry creek near Chuquisaca, Bolivia C rocky slopes with xerophilous vegetation near the town of Contumaza, Peru, habitat of narrowly endemic X. klaprothioides." figureDoi="10.3897/phytokeys.194.77827.figure4" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/673021" pageId="0" pageNumber="47">4C</figureCitation>
). Near the town of 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Contumazá">Contumaza</normalizedToken>
, it grows sympatrically with another shrubby 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Loasaceae" genus="Cylindropuntia" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="" order="Cornales" pageId="0" pageNumber="47" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Loasaceae</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Loasaceae" genus="Nasa" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Nasa macrothyrsa" order="Cornales" pageId="0" pageNumber="47" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="macrothyrsa">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="47">Nasa macrothyrsa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Urb. &amp; Gilg) Weigend. These localities are surrounded by a mosaic of fields, fallows and small patches of seasonally dry montane forest according to the 
<bibRefCitation author="Ministerio del Ambiente del Peru" journalOrPublisher="Darwiniana" pageId="0" pageNumber="47" publicationUrl="https://geoservidor.minam.gob.pe/recursos/intercambio-de-datos/" refId="B16" refString="Ministerio del Ambiente del Peru, 2015. Mapa Nacional de Cobertura Vegetal. Ministerio del ambiente del Peru. https://geoservidor.minam.gob.pe/recursos/intercambio-de-datos/" title="Mapa Nacional de Cobertura Vegetal. Ministerio del ambiente del Peru." url="https://geoservidor.minam.gob.pe/recursos/intercambio-de-datos/" year="2015">
Ministerio del Ambiente del 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Perú">Peru</normalizedToken>
(2015
</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Ministerio del Ambiente del Peru" journalOrPublisher="Darwiniana" pageId="0" pageNumber="47" publicationUrl="https://geoservidor.minam.gob.pe/recursos/intercambio-de-datos/" refId="B17" refString="Ministerio del Ambiente del Peru, 2018. Mapa Nacional de Ecosistemas. Ministerio del ambiente del Peru. https://geoservidor.minam.gob.pe/recursos/intercambio-de-datos/" title="Mapa Nacional de Ecosistemas. Ministerio del ambiente del Peru." url="https://geoservidor.minam.gob.pe/recursos/intercambio-de-datos/" year="2018">2018</bibRefCitation>
). These habitats often show signs of human alteration. 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Rodríguez-">Rodriguez-</normalizedToken>
<bibRefCitation author="Rodriguez, EF" journalOrPublisher="Numero Especial" pageId="0" pageNumber="47" pagination="391 - 402" refId="B24" refString="Rodriguez, EF, Weigend, M, 2006. Loasaceae endemicas del Peru. Revista peruana de biologia. Numero Especial 13 (2): 391 - 402" title="Loasaceae endemicas del Peru. Revista peruana de biologia." volume="13" year="2006">
<normalizedToken originalValue="Rodríguez">Rodriguez</normalizedToken>
and Weigend (2006)
</bibRefCitation>
mention that this species is found in the Mesoandina Ecological Region. 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Loasaceae" genus="Xylopodia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Xylopodia klaprothioides" order="Cornales" pageId="0" pageNumber="47" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="klaprothioides">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="47">Xylopodia klaprothioides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is deciduous and the plants shed their leaves at the beginning of flowering in May/June.
</paragraph>
